Step 1: Log Into Google Cloud CLI
Open PowerShell and run:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud auth login
This will open a browser window asking you to log into your Google account. Select the account that has access to your Google Cloud VM.

Step 2: Set Your Google Cloud Project
After logging in, set your active project:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud config set project PROJECT_ID
(Replace PROJECT_ID with your actual Google Cloud project ID.)

You can check your project ID with:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud projects list
Step 3: Verify Authentication
Run:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud auth list
It should show your logged-in account with ACTIVE next to it.

Step 4: Verify SSH Connectivity
Check if your VM exists and is running:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud compute instances list
Find your VM name and zone, then try connecting:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud compute ssh YOUR_VM_NAME --zone YOUR_VM_ZONE
(Replace YOUR_VM_NAME and YOUR_VM_ZONE with your actual VM details from the list.)

Step 5: If SSH Still Fails
Try resetting your SSH keys:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud compute os-login ssh-keys add --key-file d:\mas-ai\id_rsa.pub
Then, reconnect:

powershell
Copy
Edit
gcloud compute ssh YOUR_VM_NAME --zone YOUR_VM_ZONE --ssh-key-file=d:\mas-ai\id_rsa
